❯ Can you give me your oppinion of the website as it currently stands? 

● Let me look at the current state of the codebase to form an opinion.

  Read 9 files, listed 2 directories (ctrl+o to expand)

● Here's my honest assessment of the portfolio as it stands:

  What's Working Well

  Strong design foundation. The hex motif is distinctive and creates a memorable visual identity — it ties together the profile frame, tech grid, and project galleries into a cohesive theme. Most portfolio sites
   look interchangeable; this one won't.

  Solid technical execution. The axial coordinate hex grid with GSAP starburst hover is genuinely impressive interactive work. The sticky navbar with IntersectionObserver for both scroll-spy and stuck-state
  detection is clean. The responsive scaling system for the hex grid (60/80/100% breakpoints) is well thought out.

  Good color palette. The blue-neutral/cream-neutral/tan tones feel warm and professional without being generic. The dark navy (text-1) for the navbar and project gallery panels creates strong contrast anchors.

  Architecture is clean. Component decomposition is logical, the token system is well-organized, and the Tailwind v4 setup is modern.

  What Needs Work

  All content is placeholder. Every section — About Me, project descriptions, education — is lorem ipsum. Three identical "Hello World" project cards with the same lorem text. This is the single biggest thing
  holding the site back. A portfolio lives or dies on its content.

  Project cards feel incomplete. The hex gallery images are just the hex-base SVG (an empty shell). No actual project screenshots, no links to repos or live demos, no tech stack tags. The "Project Description"
  title is generic — should be something like "Key Features" or a descriptive heading.

  Missing sections/features:
  - No resume/CV download (there's a "See My Resume" link pointing to #resume but no resume section exists)
  - No social links (GitHub, LinkedIn) — the footer is just an empty dark bar
  - No "Skills" link in the navbar despite the Technologies section having id="skills"
  - No animations on scroll — content appears statically, which undercuts the GSAP investment elsewhere

  Minor issues:
  - vueIcon imports react.svg — wrong icon (Technologies.tsx:33)
  - "Tailwinds CSS" should be "Tailwind CSS" (Technologies.tsx:127)
  - "Java Script" / "Type Script" have errant spaces (Technologies.tsx:160-163)
  - Nav link font size (text-4xl at lg) feels oversized — competes with section headings
  - The "About Me" button in the hero has no hover state beyond shadow-lg — feels static compared to the interactive hex elements

  Overall

  The shell is strong — good design system, interesting hex concept, clean code. But it's a skeleton right now. The next push should be filling in real content (bio, projects, education), fixing the small data
  bugs, and adding the missing nav/footer links. That alone would take it from "nice demo" to "functional portfolio."
